{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f80dfcaf-dcec-4a2b-b23f-4c7140665c90","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2 which supports constructor injection for `TestContext`. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor (injected TestContext)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // synchronous setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async initialization (runs after constructor)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // async per-test setup here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        // async per-test teardown here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsTrue(true);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection**: MSTest 3.x+ injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor — no need for the legacy `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`**: Implement this for async setup that runs after construction but before each test.\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`**: Implement this for async teardown after each test.\n- The constructor handles synchronous setup; `InitializeAsync` handles anything requiring `await`.\n\nThis replaces the older `[TestInitialize]`/`[TestCleanup]` attribute-based approach while giving you both sync and async lifecycle hooks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7cee90f7-f1ed-49dd-b3c5-ef6fdb1fb055","outputTokens":403,"requestId":"BD12:2E977A:1F7FA74:23666CC:6A07CCA5"},"id":"2ba050a2-048b-4faa-9f0d-26571f88e381","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:47:28.897Z","parentId":"afc06661-f2bc-4805-a1b2-a78103cc8782"}
